{{Infobox artist | name = Birdie Alexander | image = Photo of Birdie Alexander.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1870|3|24|mf=y}} | birth_place = Lincoln County, Tennessee | death_date = {{death date and age|1960|8|2|1870|3|24|mf=y}} | death_place = El Paso, Texas | nationality = American | education = Ward Seminary | field = [[Educator]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = }}
'''Birdie Alexander''' (March 24, 1870 - August 2, 1960) was an [[United States|American]] educator and music teacher. She was a charter member of the [[National Association for Music Education|Music Supervisors' National Conference]]. Alexander is credited with laying the foundations of music education in the [[Dallas]] public schools.
== Biography == Alexander was born on March 24, 1870 in [[Lincoln County, Tennessee]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://tshaonline.org/handbook/online/articles/fal07|title=Alexander, Birdie|last=Swann|first=Lelle|date=9 June 2010|website=Handbook of Texas Online|publisher=Texas State Historical Association|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> Later, she and her family moved to Texas and she attended school in [[Forney, Texas]] and also at [[Mary Nash College]].<ref name=":0" /> She returned to Tennessee to study piano and voice at [[Ward-Belmont College|Ward Seminary]], graduating in 1891.<ref name=":0" /> When she graduated, she and her family moved to [[Dallas]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18900921/el_paso_heraldpost/|title=Miss Alexander Taken by Death|last=|first=|date=2 August 1960|work=El Paso Herald-Post|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=1|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Alexander became the [[Dallas Independent School District|Dallas Public School's]] music supervisor and worked there for twelve years during which she established a "first rate system of music education."<ref name=":1" /> She organized special concerts for students with conductor [[Walter Fried]].<ref name=":2" /> Alexander was a charter member of the [[National Association for Music Education|Music Supervisors' National Conference]], founded in 1907.<ref name=":1" /> When officials cut back on music programs, Alexander created her own music [[textbook]], published in 1912, called ''Songs We Like to Sing''.<ref name=":2" /> Alexander was also instrumental in bringing a [[Victor Talking Machine Company|victrola]] to play music for her students.<ref name=":2" /> She was also invited to lecture on music education at the [[University of Texas at Dallas|University of Texas]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3013585/el_paso_heraldpost/|title=Music Teacher Survives TB and a Broken Back|last=Carroll|first=Ann|date=21 June 1957|work=El Paso Herald-Post|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>
Alexander moved to [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] for health reasons in 1913 after contracting [[tuberculosis]].<ref name=":3" /> Her brother-in-law, Robert B. Homan, Sr., was a physician and ran a [[sanatorium]] in El Paso called [[Homan's Sanatorium|Homan's San]].<ref name=":3" /> Alexander stayed at the sanatorium for four years where she worked in the office and didn't feel that she would be able to go back to teaching music.<ref name=":3" /> Eventually, Alexander began to give piano lessons for her niece and word began to spread and soon Alexander had many students.<ref name=":3" /> There were times when she had more students than she could teach and in those situations, she would refer them to other teachers.<ref name=":3" />
Alexander was made an honorary life member of the [[Music Teachers National Association|National Music Teachers' Association]] of Texas in 1941.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/68871574|title=Miss Alexander Taken by Death|last=|first=|date=2 August 1960|work=El Paso Herald-Post|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|page=2|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Formerly, she had served as president of the organization.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18872309/el_paso_herald/|title=Miss Goff Elected Scy. Music Ass'n|last=|first=|date=28 September 1926|work=El Paso Herald|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In addition, she put together the music department for the [[Texas State Teachers Association]].<ref name=":0" />
== Death and legacy == Alexander died in her home in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]] on August 2, 1960.<ref name=":1" /> She was buried in Evergreen Cemetery in El Paso.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18872542/el_paso_heraldpost/|title=Miss Birdie Alexander|last=|first=|date=3 August 1960|work=El Paso Herald-Post|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> An [[elementary school]] named after Alexander was dedicated in [[Dallas]] in March of 1970.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?spot=3013043|title=New School Gives El Paso, Dallas a Memorial to Birdie Alexander|last=Carroll|first=Ann|date=27 February 1970|work=El Paso Herald-Post|access-date=2018-04-04|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> == References == <!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically --> {{Reflist}}
